11.              Scripting Processor

The Scripting Processor is a tool within EPPORA used by its developers and maintainers to assure that the EPPORA product satisfies each and every requirement. The execution and analysis of the test cases for a product the size of EPPORA is a timely, error-prone, expensive set of activities.   To complicate matters, nearly all software experts agree that when even a minor change is made to a software product, to verify the product prior to a release, one should re-run the entire test suite (to minimize regressions).  The EPPORA system is a complex, large application.  Since it is a tool providing critical prioritization, allocation of precious labor resources and costing data, it is imperative that the results it provides are valid and new releases can be verified in a timely manner. 

The cost of implementing the initial test suite with a scripting language is slightly more expensive than testing EPPORA by a set test engineers running the test procedures (estimated at 5-10% more).  The payoff in creating tests using the Scripting Processors occurs when the tests are run more than once.  The cost for subsequent testing is a small fraction (less than 5%) of the initial test development cost.  In addition, with the Scripting Processor, EPPORA is able to test new releases in a fraction (1/50) of the time it would have taken using multiple test engineers.   It is also easy to enhance the testing of EPPORA as new features are added or latent defects occur.

The EPPORA Scripting Language is used for specifying tests to be executed by the EPPORA Script Processor.   The scripting language simplifies the task of producing executable actions that are repeatable by the EPPORA system. The scripting language is independent of the EPPORA platform, operating or windowing system.  The scripting language can emulate any EPPORA keystroke or mouse click a user can perform by processing a text file. The text file contains a series of scripting language commands that instruct EPPORA to perform various actions, such as selecting an object, pressing a radio button, entering characters into a text edit object, selecting a check box, etc. In addition, the text-scripting file can include references to other files within it that perform additional actions.  The Scripting Processor can take a snapshot of the screen and create a stylized text file representation of the page.  The Scripting Processor can also compare two text files and report any differences.  The Scripting Processor keeps a log that lists all errors encountered, as well as other user supplied and script supplied information.  A separate document describes the Scripting Processor and is available for EPS EPPORA clients.

This page was intentionally left blank.

12.              Automated Activities

EPPORA performs numerous behind the scene activities even when there are no users.  These activities take place at the end of the business day and usually take less than an hour of wall clock time.  The activities include:

Ø  Each Project

                                          i.    Verify that a Project Manager is specified

                                         ii.    Verify that a Project Portfolio Manager is specified

                                        iii.    Verify that a Sponsor is specified

                                        iv.    Verify that the requirements are specified

                                         v.    Verify that the schedule is specified

Ø  Each Project’s Schedule

                                          i.    Verify that each task starts with a verb

                                         ii.    Verify that each low-level task has generic labor resources assigned

                                        iii.    Verify that for the allocation period each low-level task has an assigned actual resource for each required labor category

                                        iv.    Verify that the number of fixed dates for low-level task is within the organization’s threshold

                                         v.    Verify that each low-level task has no resource assigned for over the maximum effort per low-level task (default is 40 hours)

                                        vi.    Verify that no high-level tasks (parent task) has resources assigned

                                       vii.    Verify that the schedule has been updated within the “Schedule Update Period”

                                      viii.    Verify that no deliverable is late

                                        ix.    Verify that no milestone is late

                                         x.    Verify which deliverables were completed yesterday

                                        xi.    Verify which milestones were completed yesterday

Ø  Each Project’s Requirements

                                          i.    Verify that each requirement’s description contains the word “shall”

                                         ii.    Verify that each requirement’s description does not contain any adjectives

                                        iii.    Verify that each requirement’s description does not contain any adverbs

                                        iv.    Verify that each requirement’s description is not a compound statement

                                         v.    Verify that each requirement’s description does not exceed the maximum number of words allowed

                                        vi.    Verify that each low-level requirement is mapped properly to one or more project tasks

Ø  Each User

                                          i.    Verify that each user has a Supervisor specified (except if its the President)

                                         ii.    Verify that each user has one or more labor categories specified

                                        iii.    Verify that each user has a work telephone number specified

                                        iv.    Verify that each user has an email address specified

                                         v.    Verify that no user is overloaded for each day of the allocation period

Ø  Labor Categories

                                          i.    Verify that at least one labor category exist

This page was intentionally left blank.

 

13.  Limitations

This section describes each limitation within EPPORA.

 

Entry

Title

Limitation Description

1

Accumulative Mapping Task %

The accumulative mapping percentage cannot exceed 100% for a task.

2

Allocation Period

A maximum of 63 days can be specified for the allocation period.

3

Correctly Login

A user is given a maximum of 99 attempts to successfully login to EPPORA.

4

Criterion Score Maximum

The maximum score for a project’s criterion is 10.

5

Criterion Score Minimum

The minimum score for a project’s criterion is 0.

6

Criterion Weight Maximum

The maximum criterion weight is 5.

7

Criterion Weight Minimum

The minimum criterion weight is -5.

8

End-of-Business

During the “End-of-Business” period no users may be logged in to EPPORA.

9

Labor Category Name

The maximum size of a labor category name is 255 characters.

10

Maximum Task Days

The maximum acceptable days for a low-level task are 60 days.

11

Multiple Logins

At any instance a user may only be logged into EPPORA once.

12

Number Labor Categories

The maximum number of active labor categories is 65,535.

13

Number Projects

The maximum number of active projects is 65,535.

14

Number Users

The maximum number of active users is 1,048,575.

15

Password Validity

The duration for a password being valid for each user is 365 days.

16

Project Duration

The maximum duration for a project cannot exceed 15 years.

17

Project Name

The maximum size of a project name is 255 characters.

18

Project Requirements Maximum

The maximum number of project requirements is 232-1.

19

Project Tasks Maximum

The maximum number of project tasks is 232-1.

20

User Defined Criteria

A maximum of 13 user defined criteria can be specified.

21

User Name

The maximum size of a user name is 255 characters.
